As used in this section:
"Approved time" means a period of time beginning on July 26, 2009, and ending on December 31, 2010;
"New home tax credit cap" means a maximum of fifteen million dollars ($15,000,000) allocated to qualified buyers on a first-come, first-served basis;
"Purchase" means a point within the approved time when escrow closes between the qualified buyer and the seller of the qualified principal residence;
"Qualified buyer" means a resident who purchases a qualified principal residence; and
"Qualified principal residence" means a single-family dwelling which is:
Either detached or attached;
Certified by the seller as having never been occupied; and
Purchased to be the principal residence of the qualified buyer for a minimum of two (2) years.

To administer the new home tax credit and new home tax credit cap, the department shall:
Create the application required to be filed by a qualified buyer;
Promulgate administrative regulations to administer the new home tax credit, including but not limited to:
The process of recapture of the credit if the qualified buyer does not maintain the new home as his or her principal residence for two (2) years; and
How to allocate the new home tax credit between unmarried co-purchasers or between married individuals who file separate returns;
Create a Web site containing the amount of the total credit allocated to date, the date the last processed application was received, and the remaining credit available to qualified buyers;
Establish a dedicated telephone line to receive faxed applications;
Allow the date and time stamp from the faxed application as the order within which the application was received; and
Notify the qualified buyer of the allowable credit available to the qualified buyer by a credit allocation letter, which shall be submitted by the qualified buyer with his or her return.

The application for the new home tax credit shall be void if:
The home has been previously occupied;
The application is not received within seven (7) calendar days from the purchase;
The application is not received within thirty (30) calendar days from June 4, 2010, for purchases of a qualified principal residence after November 6, 2009, but before June 4, 2010; or
The application is received after the new home tax credit cap has been reached.
